PHASE 3: DEPLOY TO CLIENT COMPUTERS
Step 3.1: Prerequisites for Each Client Computer
Before installing on each client computer, ensure:
1.	Windows 7 SP1 or later (Windows 10/11 recommended)
2.	.NET Framework 4.7.2 or later:
•	Most Windows 10/11 computers have this pre-installed
•	If not installed, download from: https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download/dotnet-framework/net472
3.	Network connectivity to the server
---
Step 3.2: Install Application on Client Computer
1.	Copy the Installer:
•	Copy StorePartsSetup_v1.0.0.exe to a USB drive or network share
2.	Run the Installer on each client computer:
•	Double-click StorePartsSetup_v1.0.0.exe
•	If prompted by Windows Defender/UAC, click Yes or Run anyway
•	Follow the installation wizard:
•	Click Next
•	Accept default installation folder (or choose custom)
•	Click Next
•	Check "Create desktop shortcut" if desired
•	Click Install
•	Wait for installation to complete
•	Check "Launch Store Parts" and click Finish
---
Step 3.3: Configure Database Connection on Each Client
When the application launches for the first time:
1.	You'll see the Login screen with a message about database connection
2.	Click "Configure Database" button
3.	Enter the following details:
| Field | Value | |-------|-------| | Server Name | SERVER_IP\SQLEXPRESS (e.g., 192.168.1.100\SQLEXPRESS) | | Database Name | MainDB | | Authentication | Windows Authentication (recommended) |
Example Server Names:
•	If server IP is 192.168.1.100: Enter 192.168.1.100\SQLEXPRESS
•	If server computer name is OFFICE-SERVER: Enter OFFICE-SERVER\SQLEXPRESS
4.	Click "Test Connection":
•	If successful: You'll see "Connection successful!" in green
•	If failed: Check server IP, firewall settings, and SQL Server configuration
5.	Click "Save and Connect":
•	The connection settings will be saved
•	Database tables will be created if needed
6.	Login to the Application:
•	Username: admin
•	Password: admin
---
PHASE 4: VERIFICATION & TESTING
Step 4.1: Test from Server Computer
1.	Launch Store Parts on the server
2.	Login with admin/admin
3.	Add a test entry:
•	Click Add New
•	Enter Challan No: TEST001
•	Select Party and Item
•	Enter Qty: 10
•	Click Save
4.	Verify the entry appears in the grid
Step 4.2: Test from Client Computer
1.	Launch Store Parts on a client computer
2.	Login with admin/admin
3.	Verify you can see the test entry created from the server
4.	Add another entry from the client
5.	Go back to the server and verify the new entry appears
Step 4.3: Test Multi-User Access
1.	Have multiple users logged in simultaneously
2.	One user adds an entry
3.	Other users click Refresh and verify they see the new entry
---
PHASE 5: BACKUP & MAINTENANCE
Step 5.1: Create Backup Script
Create a batch file on the server named BackupDatabase.bat:

@echo off
REM ============================================
REM Store Parts Database Backup Script
REM ============================================
REM Run this script daily to backup your database
REM Schedule using Windows Task Scheduler
REM ============================================

setlocal

REM Configuration - MODIFY THESE VALUES
set SERVER_NAME=.\SQLEXPRESS
set DATABASE_NAME=MainDB
set BACKUP_FOLDER=C:\DatabaseBackups\StoreParts
set DAYS_TO_KEEP=30

REM Create backup folder if it doesn't exist
if not exist "%BACKUP_FOLDER%" mkdir "%BACKUP_FOLDER%"

REM Generate timestamp for filename
set TIMESTAMP=%date:~-4%%date:~4,2%%date:~7,2%_%time:~0,2%%time:~3,2%%time:~6,2%
set TIMESTAMP=%TIMESTAMP: =0%

REM Set backup filename
set BACKUP_FILE=%BACKUP_FOLDER%\%DATABASE_NAME%_%TIMESTAMP%.bak

echo ============================================
echo Store Parts Database Backup
echo ============================================
echo Date/Time: %date% %time%
echo Server: %SERVER_NAME%
echo Database: %DATABASE_NAME%
echo Backup File: %BACKUP_FILE%
echo ============================================
echo.

REM Perform backup using sqlcmd
echo Creating backup...
sqlcmd -S %SERVER_NAME% -E -Q "BACKUP DATABASE [%DATABASE_NAME%] TO DISK='%BACKUP_FILE%' WITH FORMAT, INIT, NAME='%DATABASE_NAME% Full Backup', SKIP, NOREWIND, NOUNLOAD, STATS=10"

if %ERRORLEVEL% EQU 0 (
    echo.
    echo Backup completed successfully!
    echo File: %BACKUP_FILE%
    
    REM Get file size
    for %%A in ("%BACKUP_FILE%") do echo Size: %%~zA bytes
) else (
    echo.
    echo ERROR: Backup failed! Error code: %ERRORLEVEL%
    echo Please check SQL Server is running and accessible.
)

echo.
echo ============================================
echo Cleaning up old backups (older than %DAYS_TO_KEEP% days)...
echo ============================================

REM Delete backups older than specified days
forfiles /p "%BACKUP_FOLDER%" /s /m *.bak /d -%DAYS_TO_KEEP% /c "cmd /c del @path && echo Deleted: @file" 2>nul

echo.
echo Backup process complete.
echo ============================================

REM Log to file
echo %date% %time% - Backup completed: %BACKUP_FILE% >> "%BACKUP_FOLDER%\backup_log.txt"

endlocal
pause

---
Step 5.2: Create Restore Script
Create a batch file on the server named RestoreDatabase.bat:

@echo off
REM ============================================
REM Store Parts Database Restore Script
REM ============================================
REM Use this script to restore from a backup file
REM WARNING: This will OVERWRITE existing data!
REM ============================================

setlocal

REM Configuration - MODIFY THESE VALUES
set SERVER_NAME=.\SQLEXPRESS
set DATABASE_NAME=MainDB
set BACKUP_FOLDER=C:\DatabaseBackups\StoreParts

echo ============================================
echo Store Parts Database Restore
echo ============================================
echo.
echo WARNING: This will OVERWRITE all current data!
echo.

REM List available backups
echo Available backup files:
echo ----------------------
dir /b /o-d "%BACKUP_FOLDER%\*.bak" 2>nul
echo.

REM Prompt for backup file
set /p BACKUP_FILE="Enter backup filename (e.g., MainDB_20240101_120000.bak): "

REM Validate file exists
if not exist "%BACKUP_FOLDER%\%BACKUP_FILE%" (
    echo.
    echo ERROR: Backup file not found: %BACKUP_FOLDER%\%BACKUP_FILE%
    pause
    exit /b 1
)

echo.
echo You are about to restore: %BACKUP_FILE%
echo This will OVERWRITE all current data in %DATABASE_NAME%!
echo.
set /p CONFIRM="Are you sure? Type YES to continue: "

if /i not "%CONFIRM%"=="YES" (
    echo.
    echo Restore cancelled.
    pause
    exit /b 0
)

echo.
echo ============================================
echo Starting restore process...
echo ============================================

REM Set database to single user mode to disconnect all users
echo Setting database to single user mode...
sqlcmd -S %SERVER_NAME% -E -Q "ALTER DATABASE [%DATABASE_NAME%] SET SINGLE_USER WITH ROLLBACK IMMEDIATE"

REM Perform restore
echo Restoring database from backup...
sqlcmd -S %SERVER_NAME% -E -Q "RESTORE DATABASE [%DATABASE_NAME%] FROM DISK='%BACKUP_FOLDER%\%BACKUP_FILE%' WITH REPLACE, STATS=10"

if %ERRORLEVEL% EQU 0 (
    echo.
    echo Restore completed successfully!
) else (
    echo.
    echo ERROR: Restore failed! Error code: %ERRORLEVEL%
)

REM Set database back to multi user mode
echo Setting database back to multi user mode...
sqlcmd -S %SERVER_NAME% -E -Q "ALTER DATABASE [%DATABASE_NAME%] SET MULTI_USER"

echo.
echo ============================================
echo Restore process complete.
echo ============================================

REM Log to file
echo %date% %time% - Restore completed from: %BACKUP_FILE% >> "%BACKUP_FOLDER%\restore_log.txt"

endlocal
pause

---
Step 5.3: Schedule Automatic Backups
1.	Open Task Scheduler:
•	Press Windows + R
•	Type: taskschd.msc
•	Press Enter
2.	Create a New Task:
•	Click "Create Task..." in the right panel
3.	General Tab:
•	Name: Store Parts Daily Backup
•	Description: Automated daily backup of MainDB database
•	Check "Run whether user is logged on or not"
•	Check "Run with highest privileges"
4.	Triggers Tab:
•	Click New...
•	Begin the task: On a schedule
•	Settings: Daily
•	Start time: 11:00 PM (or your preferred time)
•	Recur every: 1 day
•	Click OK
5.	Actions Tab:
•	Click New...
•	Action: Start a program
•	Program/script: C:\DatabaseBackups\BackupDatabase.bat
•	Click OK
6.	Settings Tab:
•	Check "Allow task to be run on demand"
•	Check "Run task as soon as possible after a scheduled start is missed"
•	Click OK
7.	Enter your Windows password when prompted
8.	Test the Task:
•	Right-click the task → Run
•	Check C:\DatabaseBackups\StoreParts\ for backup files
---
Step 5.4: Database Maintenance Tasks
Run these SQL commands monthly in SSMS for optimal performance:

-- ============================================
-- Monthly Database Maintenance Script
-- ============================================

USE MainDB;
GO

-- Update statistics for better query performance
EXEC sp_updatestats;
PRINT 'Statistics updated.';
GO

-- Rebuild indexes to reduce fragmentation
ALTER INDEX ALL ON machinery_item_inward_unit2 REBUILD;
ALTER INDEX ALL ON PartyMaster REBUILD;
ALTER INDEX ALL ON ItemMaster REBUILD;
ALTER INDEX ALL ON MachineMaster REBUILD;
ALTER INDEX ALL ON PersonMaster REBUILD;
PRINT 'Indexes rebuilt.';
GO

-- Shrink log file if needed (use sparingly)
DBCC SHRINKFILE (MainDB_log, 100);
PRINT 'Log file maintenance complete.';
GO

PRINT 'Monthly maintenance complete!';
GO

---
PHASE 6: TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE
Issue 6.1: Cannot Connect to Database from Client
Symptoms:
•	"Connection failed" error
•	"Server not found" error
•	Connection timeout

Solutions:
1.	Verify Server IP Address:
•	On server, run: ipconfig
•	Confirm client is using correct IP address
2.	Test Network Connectivity:
•	On client, open Command Prompt
•	Run: ping SERVER_IP (e.g., ping 192.168.1.100)
•	Should see replies, not "Request timed out"
3.	Test SQL Server Port:
•	On client, open Command Prompt
•	Run: telnet SERVER_IP 1433
•	If it connects (blank screen), port is open
•	If "Could not open connection", firewall is blocking
4.	Verify Firewall Rules:
•	On server, ensure ports 1433 (TCP) and 1434 (UDP) are open
•	Temporarily disable firewall to test
5.	Check SQL Server Services:
•	On server, open Services (services.msc)
•	Ensure "SQL Server (SQLEXPRESS)" is Running
•	Ensure "SQL Server Browser" is Running
---
Issue 6.2: Application Won't Start
Symptoms:
•	Application crashes on startup
•	No error message appears
•	Application hangs

Solutions:
1.	Check .NET Framework:
•	Open Command Prompt as Administrator
•	Run: reg query "HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\NET Framework Setup\NDP\v4\Full" /v Release
•	Value should be 461808 or higher for .NET 4.7.2
2.	Reinstall Application:
•	Uninstall via Control Panel
•	Delete remaining files in C:\Program Files\Store Parts\
•	Reinstall from installer
3.	Check Event Viewer:
•	Press Windows + R
•	Type: eventvwr.msc
•	Check Windows Logs → Application for errors
4.	Run as Administrator:
•	Right-click application → Run as administrator
---
Issue 6.3: Database Connection Lost During Use
Symptoms:
•	"Connection lost" error during operation
•	Data not saving
•	Application freezes when saving

Solutions:
1.	Check Network Stability:
•	Ensure network cables are secure
•	Check for network outages
2.	Increase Connection Timeout:
•	In Database Configuration, increase timeout value
3.	Check SQL Server Resources:
•	On server, open Task Manager
•	Check CPU and Memory usage
•	SQL Server should not be at 100% CPU
4.	Restart SQL Server Service:
•	On server, open Services
•	Restart "SQL Server (SQLEXPRESS)"
---
Issue 6.4: Slow Application Performance
Symptoms:
•	Slow data loading
•	Long wait times when saving
•	Grid takes time to populate

Solutions:
1.	Check Network Speed:
•	Ensure gigabit network if possible
•	Avoid WiFi for database connections
2.	Run Database Maintenance:
•	Execute monthly maintenance script (Step 5.4)
3.	Check Database Size:
•	In SSMS, right-click database → Properties → Files
•	If very large, consider archiving old data
4.	Add Indexes (Advanced):
•	Contact IT support for index optimization
---
Issue 6.5: Login Problems
Symptoms:
•	Cannot login with admin/admin
•	"Invalid credentials" error

Solutions:
1.	Verify Default Credentials:
•	Username: admin
•	Password: admin (case-sensitive)
2.	Reset Admin Password:
•	In SSMS, run:
USE MainDB;
UPDATE Users SET password = 'admin' WHERE username = 'admin';
3.	Check Users Table Exists:
•	In SSMS, verify Users table contains admin account
---
PHASE 7: ADVANCED CONFIGURATION
Step 7.1: SQL Server Authentication (Optional)
If Windows Authentication doesn't work, use SQL Server Authentication:
1.	Enable Mixed Mode Authentication:
•	Open SSMS
•	Right-click server → Properties
•	Security page → Server authentication
•	Select "SQL Server and Windows Authentication mode"
•	Click OK
•	Restart SQL Server service
2.	Create SQL Server Login:
USE [master]
GO
CREATE LOGIN [StorePartsUser] WITH PASSWORD = 'YourSecurePassword123!';
GO
USE [MainDB]
GO
CREATE USER [StorePartsUser] FOR LOGIN [StorePartsUser];
GO
ALTER ROLE [db_owner] ADD MEMBER [StorePartsUser];
GO
3.	Configure Application:
•	In Database Configuration form
•	Select "SQL Server Authentication"
•	Enter Username: StorePartsUser
•	Enter Password: YourSecurePassword123!
---
Step 7.2: Configure Static IP on Server (Recommended)
To prevent IP address changes:
1.	Open Network Settings:
•	Press Windows + R
•	Type: ncpa.cpl
•	Press Enter
2.	Configure Adapter:
•	Right-click network adapter → Properties
•	Select "Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4)" → Properties
•	Select "Use the following IP address"
•	Enter:
    •	IP address: 192.168.1.100 (example)
    •	Subnet mask: 255.255.255.0
    •	Default gateway: 192.168.1.1 (your router)
    •	Preferred DNS: 8.8.8.8
•	Click OK
---
Step 7.3: Remote Desktop Access to Server
For remote server management:
1.	Enable Remote Desktop on Server:
•	Press Windows + R
•	Type: SystemPropertiesRemote
•	Select "Allow remote connections to this computer"
•	Click OK
2.	Allow Through Firewall:
•	Windows Firewall should automatically allow RDP
•	Port 3389 TCP
3.	Connect from Client:
•	Press Windows + R
•	Type: mstsc
•	Enter server IP address
•	Login with server credentials
---
PHASE 8: USER MANAGEMENT
Step 8.1: Creating Additional Users
To add new users to the system:
1.	Login as Admin
2.	Go to Settings → User Management
3.	Click "Add User"
4.	Enter:
•	Username
•	Password
•	Role (Admin/User)
5.	Click Save
Step 8.2: Changing Passwords
1.	Login to the application
2.	Go to Settings → Change Password
3.	Enter current password
4.	Enter new password
5.	Confirm new password
6.	Click Save
